  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity worldwide. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal or \"clean.\" This is typically done through a series of complex transactions or financial maneuvers to obscure the original source of the funds.\n\nMost countries have stringent laws and regulations in place to combat money laundering. For example:\n\n1. **United States**: The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and the USA PATRIOT Act impose requirements on financial institutions to detect and report suspicious activities.\n2. **European Union**: The EU has multiple Anti-Money Laundering (AML) directives that set out measures to prevent money laundering and terrorist financing.\n3. **China**: The Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China provides the legal framework for combating money laundering activities.\n\nInternational organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) also work to set global standards and promote effective implementation of measures to combat money laundering and terrorist financing. Legal penalties for money laundering can include heavy fines, imprisonment, and other sanctions.",
